title: For Sale:  Mauser Sporter rifle + ammo & extras
location: University Area, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: Mauser Sporter hunting rifle, built years ago from a Yugoslav M48 Mauser military rifle.  Carbine configuration, with a 17" barrel.  The rifle action was built, as near as I can determine, about 1951.  The stock is a nice walnut one, made from a Yugoslav 24/47 original.  The stock was probably made sometime in the 1930's (based on a cartouche found on the butt). Tiger striping in the butt of the stock - this is a very nice piece of walnut.  The rifle is in very good condition, no rust.....and the finish is in good shape for it's age.  The rifle was re-barreled several years ago,  in the original 8mm Mauser (7.92 x 57 JS) chambering.  The barrel is in very good shape.The action has been glass-bedded into the stock.The rifle wears a Japanese-made Weaver Classic LER scope,  2.5 - 8 X 28.   The trigger is a Timney Sportsman, single stage,  set to 3.0 lbs.  This is a good all round,  absolutely reliable shooter and great classic hunting rifle.  It will produce about 1.5" groups at 100 yards at best.  "Normal" groups are about 2", with my current hand loads.  Included with the rifle are a scope cover,  leather sling and a soft case.  Also included are approximately 600 rounds of 8mm Mauser hand loaded ammo (170 grain soft point hunting loads).  Further, I will include some additional 8mm Mauser brass,  1 box of Speer 150 grain SP bullets.....and a complete set of Lee reloading dies.  The ammo alone, if estimating only $10 per box (at which price you'd NEVER find it these days).......is worth more than $300,  by itself.  The scope is only about 1 month old......and cost $240.The Timney trigger cost $60.  I am offering all of the above at $550.  The price is somewhat negotiable,  but only somewhat.  All obvious "low-ball" offers will be ignored (no response will be made)......so unless you are serious, don't make an offer.  I will NOT ship the rifle or other items, due to the weight (and therefore, the cost).  Face to face meeting only.  I will travel a reasonable distance to meet a buyer - a reasonable distance - but I expect the buyer to make an effort also.  The rifle is NOT a "collector rifle"..... and that is why I am pricing it very reasonably.  I am selling it because A) I no longer hunt.......and B) I am getting a bit old and can no longer tolerate the recoil.  Finally, a Bill of Sale will be provided.  The buyer will need a valid photo ID (which information will be listed on the Bill of Sale)......and both parties will sign said Bill of Sale.  All relevant laws WILL be complied with - no exceptions.

title: For Sale:  Walther CCP SS
postcontent: The CCP’s SOFTCOIL™ gas-delayed blowback system uses gas pressure from the ignited cartridge by directing it through a small port in the barrel in front of the chamber to slow down and delay the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined after the bullet has left the barrel. This allows the slide to end its rearward motion, opening the breech, and ejecting the empty cartridge case.

title: For Sale:  Star Firestar .45 cal
postcontent: Star Firestar .45 cal**60 DAY LAYAWAY** Condition Used looks new minor wear and tear in box with 2 mags Price $300**Harvey Special  Inventory # G-19213-1 Manufacturer Star Model Firestar Caliber .45 cal Type Pistol Barrel Length 3.75in Fun Fact The Firestar series is a group of small, compact pistols designed for concealed carry. These are interesting in several ways. First of all, in that there is a true series. Not one that emerged over time as variants were introducted, but a series conceived and sold all at the same time. This offered small, single-stack pistols in 9 mm Parabellum, .40 S&Wand .45 ACP, and a double-column — but otherwise identical — 9 mm as well. Secondly, these are a mix of mechanical features. Though constructed firmly in the modern era, they are still single action. Slide rails are inverted, and the locking system is generally of the most modern styling, with coned barrels which did not otherwise emerge until the M31 and Megastar. The trigger system is, however, almost identical to that of the classic series, even forsaking the removable backstrap of the modern series pistols. Other mechanical differences include the lack of a firing pin stop plate. To remove the firing pin, the rear sight must be removed (by hammering it off), and the drop safety pull out the top. The trigger is basically that of the 1911 clones like the B series, and retains the disappointing single side transfer bar. Although I can only surmise the point of these guns was to capture the same concealed carry market the then-discontinued PD blazed, they never achieved the same following. Though reasonably popular sellers, by the time they emerged, there were a number of competitors, including a large selection of increasingly compact 1911s. They were also rather heavy by comparison, and the only alloy-framed pistol offered was the double-stack M234. I do not have manuals for every pistol shown on this site. However, in many cases there is a related manual. Partly to make the series relationships clearer, and partly to assist with speed and accuracy of updating, all manuals can be found in one place, the manuals page. All manuals available are provided as downloadable PDFs, or you may purchase a printed copy of the entire set of handgun manuals. There is one good warning not included in the manuals. Use some caution when stripping these pistols. The safety lever is only prevented from over-rotating by the grip panels. If they are removed for cleaning or maintenance, the safety can be rotated too far, and the the detent plunger will fly out. This is a very, very, small part and will almost certainly become lost. The safety lever is very important to the safe operation of the gun, so use caution not to lose the detent pin. If you do loose this part, a very tiny ball bearing can replace it perfectly well, but good luck getting ahold of one.
